When Cameron took the lead in 2005, he said he wanted to move away from the kind of political theatre that is often associated with Prime Minister Question Time, but he later had to admit that he had failed.
Since they began to be televised in 1990, the Prime Minister’s Question Time has been an important indicator of the leader’s discretion, his control of the House of Commons, and his position among other members of parliament, even though critics have criticized Question Time as becoming a travesty that requires far-reaching reforms.
