Metcash launches grassroots campaign against Aldi intrusion
Metcash is trying to protect its IGA trades from Aldi's invasion of southern and western Australia.
Food wholesaler Metcash has launched a grassroots campaign to defend the market share of IGA traders in southern and western Australia before Aldi’s $700 million attack.
Aldi is preparing to open two distribution centers as well as its first store early next year in Southern and Western Australia, with up to 120 stores in the pipeline. Meanwhile, Metcash and IGA supermarkets are strengthening their relationships with local food vendors and building the IGA brand through mainstream and social media marketing, as well as events such as the Adelaide show.
IGA merchants and suppliers have jumped in, and brands like Dunsborough ice cream maker Simmo's are offering tastings at IGA stores, and store owners are selling discounted tickets to Australian football matches to their regular customers.
Metcash is expected to reveal more details about its defense strategy on September 29, as this food, alcohol and hardware wholesaler hosts its annual Investor Strategy Day.
There is a lot at stake, as Southern and Western Australia together account for almost 30% of Metcash’s IGA trading territory, with higher profit margins than the IGA network in the eastern states of Metcash.
Shoppers in South and West Australia are known to be parochial, with IGA retailers having a much higher market share than New South Wales, Victoria and Queensland: more than 30% in the South and 24% in the West, compared to 14% in the East.
However, analysts such as Morgan Stanley believe that Aldi will capture about 5 percent of the food market in these two states within 12 months of the first stores opening.
In a report this week, Morgan Stanley analyst Tom Kierath estimates that IGA dealers could lose $360 million annually on sales and Metcash could lose $250 million by the end of 2016.
This forecast is based on the assumption that Aldi will open 25 stores in the south and 30 in the west next year, generating $500 million and $600 million in revenue in these areas.
The loss of food and food sales and volumes at Metcash’s high fixed-cost base could cost Metcash about $13 million in operating profit losses before interest and taxes, Kierath said.
At the same time, Metcash is losing market share in the Eastern Länder mainly to Aldi and Coles, although a recent study by Roy Morgan found that IGA customers were the most loyal.
Morgan Stanley believes that Metcash’s food and food sales will fall by 3.8% in 2016; 4.1% in 2017 and 2.1% in 2018, so that its market share will fall from 14% in 2015 to 10.3% in 2020.
Last week, Hamish Douglass, manager of a leading investment fund and founder of Magellan Financial Group, said during a business lunch in Melbourne that Metcash could “very possibly lose in a decade.”
Metcash has refused to respond publicly to Douglass’ comments.
However, it is understood that a member of the Metcash board would have contacted Douglass last week.
Since 2010, IGA’s market share has fallen from 18 % to 14 %, and profits from Metcash’s food and food business, which distributes products to around 1200 IGA retailers, have fallen by 43 % since 2012, reflecting a reduction in the debt financing of operations as sales and margins are under pressure.
However, the wholesaler stands his ground, and has invested more than $150 million annually in bringing prices of hundreds of products weekly down to par with those of Coles and Woolworths, helping IGA retailers refurbish stores by adding more fast-growing fresh food, and bringing a better range of private label products to the market.
Metcash CEO Ian Morrice says that lowering prices and improving stores have increased the appeal, and he hopes the wholesaler will return to the path of revenue growth in 2017, for the first time in four years.
