The video shows how the nematodes change direction as soon as the sound impulse hits them.
Scientists have bred worms with genetically modified nervous systems to control them through sound-wave bursts.
The tiny nematodes change direction as soon as they are hit by a sound impulse that is too high for the human ear to hear.
The impulses work by switching on genetically modified motor neurons with membrane channels that react to ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists Read and Write Brain Activity with Light
The researchers said that the worms demonstrate the functionality of a new method called sound genetics, in which ultrasound can be used to activate certain brain, heart and muscle cells from outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told The Guardian that the method could one day replace deep brain stimulation, an invasive procedure that sends electrical impulses to people’s brains to treat Parkinson’s disease.
Nematodes do not normally respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that when they are surrounded by a liquid with microscopic bubbles, the situation changed.
He found that the bubbles amplified ultrasonic waves, which then travel inside the worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves affect the TRP-4 ion channels, structures found in the cell membranes of some worms.
Sound waves cause these ion channels to open and activate attached cells, reports a report in the journal Nature Communications.
In order to produce ultrasonically-guided nematodes, Chalasani genetically engineered the worms so that some of their motor neurons have TRP-4 ion channels.
When Chalasani applied ultrasound to the modified worms, the microbubbles amplified the sound waves and transmitted them to the worms, where they switched on the modified motion neurons.
The method has some of the same features as optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn nerve cells on and off using light pulses.
However, Chalasani says that there may be some advantages to using sonogenetics over optogenetics.
Unlike light, which must be sent along optical fiber to the desired location inside the brain, low-frequency ultrasound waves can pass through the tissue unhindered, so they can be sent to the brain from the top of the skull.
"We believe that by using gene therapy and a therapeutic virus, it may be possible to make the targeted human nerve cells momentarily respond to an ultrasound signal in certain neurological treatments in a clinical setting," Chalasani said.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
