U.S. Fed to try to tighten monetary policy
The next recession in the U.S. will begin in less than a year, but more likely in three years, after the Fed starts raising interest rates again.
And in the financial markets, the recession begins before the next recession.
The Fed has hinted that it may begin raising interest rates this week and by the end of the year at the latest.
Thus, the next recession could topple at its fastest by next autumn and the financial markets before that.
Or at least that is what will happen if the world’s largest economy and financial markets act as they used to – and react to the Fed’s tightening of its money taps as they have done in the past.
These are the conclusions reached by Deutsche Bank London market research strategists Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker in their extensive study of long-term market and economic cycles.
The bank distributed a 60-page long-term asset return study to major international customers last week.
The strategists who produced the study and report do not pretend to know exactly when the Fed will start raising interest rates or what will happen in the economy and markets thereafter.
Instead, they use cool facts and calculations from economic statistics to show how the economy and markets have behaved in the past during and after the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
In addition to historical observations, they look at which key variables in the economy and financial markets are now on the same or a different model than they were at the time of the previous interest rate hikes – and what the possible consequences might be.
It is clear that both the economy and the financial markets are now in a shaky condition to withstand the rise in interest rates than at any time since the 1950s.
Maybe not even a year into the recession.
Throughout last summer and early autumn, the Fed’s monetary policy and its current stance have been hinting that the time is ripe to raise interest rates.
The first increase in interest rates in more than nine years could come as early as this week.
The matter will be resolved during Wednesday and Thursday, when the Fed's Board of Governors, the so-called Open Market Committee, meets to decide on the matter for its two-day meeting.
The last time the Fed raised its so-called Fed funds steering rate was in June 2006.
That marked the end of exactly two years of relatively regular, but small, 0.25-percentage-point hikes in which the Fed raised its interest rate from 1.25% to 5.25%.
Financial market turmoil began in 2007 with the most risky housing financing in the United States, and a year later, the financial crisis erupted into a global doomsday nightmare.
The Great Recession came in 2009.
Last time, the severe setbacks in the financial markets and the real economy started at a slower pace than has typically been the case since the previous Fed interest rate hikes.
Similarly, the trials were harder and more severe than at any time since the depression of the 1930’s.
Deutsche’s strategists have screened the rise and fall of the world’s largest economies and financial markets since 1950, and in some places since the early 19th century.
They have been reporting on the Fed’s interest rate hikes and their economic and financial impact since the 1950s.
At its fastest, less than a year has passed since the first interest rate hike, usually less than three years and less than three and a half years on average.
The rise in the financial markets has ended within a year or two of the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
Since the early 1950s, the Fed has in turn raised and lowered its policy rate for a dozen cycles of varying lengths.
Each occasion has differed from the others in some respects, and the narrator is relatively scarce in the examination, so it is hardly possible to infer from them anything certain about the effects of subsequent interest rate increases.
But this time, many things are different.
And not just better.
Interest rates too low for too long
The decisive causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, cannot necessarily be established even by decades of research.
But three reasons that led to the crisis and increased its destructive power are probably somewhat indisputably clear:
1) In the 21st century, the Fed, the ECB and other major central banks in the world kept their key interest rates too low for too long.
They patched up the traces of the techno-bubble, while growing the next one.
2) Over the decades, the already excessive amounts of debt accumulated in various parts of the financial and real economy grew even larger as a result of the excessive monetary policy of the central banks.
It was the largest debt bubble in economic history.
3) In particular, the almost unchecked lunatic debt financing of the financial economy inflated some of the biggest bubbles in the history of the financial markets, from equities to real estate, bonds and commodities.
There is hardly any serious controversy about the fact that the financial markets, soaring to heights with increasingly complex leverage, were in an unusually dangerous and volatile state when the Fed and other central banks last pushed interest rates up.
The debt-leveraged financial structures, let alone valuation bubbles, lasted only a short time after the interest rate hikes had begun and the costs of debt financing had started to rise.
Risks materialised as a financial crisis, followed by a major recession.
More money and more debt
Deutsche's strategists do not speculate on what will happen next, but give cause for thought by mentioning, for example, the following factors:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now considered their monetary policy stance to be more accommodative for even longer than before the financial crisis.
If interest rates were too low for too long before the crisis, they have now been even lower for even longer.
2) Indebtedness has not been as cheap for a long time as it was ten years ago, and now debt money is literally cheaper than free money.
As a result, the debt burden of the financial and real economy has not eased, but the debt burden in different parts of the economy is now much heavier than before the financial crisis or towards it at any time before.
(3) Central bank liquidity has for the most part remained in the financial markets, leaving the most important classes of securities and assets at their highest prices since the peak before the financial crisis or at any time.
And strategists are not only plaguing the mood with warning signals from the financial markets, but they are also pointing out that even the US economy has not yet recovered from the financial crisis and from the worst recession in decades to the model it has seen in the past.
The euro area economy has barely recovered.
In other words, the real economy is in an unusually weak state, but correspondingly, financial market pressures and risks are incomparably greater than they were before the financial crisis, when the Fed next starts tightening its taps.
Perhaps Albert Edwards, the strategist of the French bank Societe Generale, is not as strange as it may seem.
For a long time, he has been training the bank’s international investor clients for the following U-turns of the Fed:
First the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles burst - and soon the Fed will have time to put out the financial fires with even bigger QE money syringes.
