Federal Reserve policymakers are sitting around a huge mahogany table for two days this week in a long-awaited meeting to decide whether the time has come to raise the policy rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At the other end of the central bank’s decorative two-story meeting room is a mural of the United States.
The map is a reminder that Central Bank President Janet L. Yellen and her colleagues must put the nation’s financial interests first.
Congress has placed a dual responsibility on the central bank: to maximize U.S. employment and keep prices stable.
After the Great Depression, however, central bank governors have accepted that there is a third unwritten mandate: financial stability.
It is this third requirement that could be the deciding factor in a decision that is so tight that it cannot even be predicted, a decision on whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the record incentive brought about by the near-zero short-term interest rate since late 2008.
While most of the data shows that the economy is growing steadily, the recent turmoil in global financial markets may have made already wary central bank officials even more alarmed when it comes to increasing volatility. There are fears about what would happen if the federal funds rate were to be raised even by a quarter of a percentage point.
“Obviously, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important factors to be monitored,” says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief financial officer at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
“However, I believe that if they are looking for a justification for leaving interest rates unchanged, increased uncertainty in the global market is a valid reason to wait yet,” he says.
No agreement has been reached on the central bank’s decision, which in itself causes nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent study by Bloomberg, about half of economists predict that interest rates will rise this week.
The financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the withdrawal, as the key indicator shows that there is only a 30% chance of growth.
This suggests a decline in the securities market if the central bank raises the level, unless the decision-makers then manage to soften the blow by promising that the next drawdown will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 228.89 points, or 1.4 percent, to 16,599.85.
The recovery was driven by expectations that the central bank would maintain its level this week, said John Lonski, chief economist at Moody's Capital Markets Research Group.
“It’s surprising if the central bank is raising interest rates right now,” he says.
If policymakers raise interest rates, “they will have to make a lot of effort in their policy to support the financial markets so that they don’t panic.”
Other experts argue that an elevated level would calm the financial markets because it would remove uncertainty about when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it appeared that the Central Bank would be raising interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step towards a slow tightening of the monetary situation that would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that she expects the level to rise this year, despite the fact that the Liberals are calling for more economic development in their election.
Although job creation slowed in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell to 5.1% last month, the lowest in seven years and close to what the central bank considers the threshold for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of recovery.
Although inflation is still below the central bank’s annual target of 2%, central bank policymakers say the main reason for this is the temporary impact of the much lower oil price.
The economy "sees higher interest rates and needs them, given the tight labour market situation", says Ian Shepherdson, chief economist at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell by up to 16 percent from its May record, as investors feared China’s slowing economy would also slow global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now nearly 10 percent below its May peak.
For central bank decision-makers, market turmoil is an additional factor in the complex equation of when interest rates should be raised.
“Without these financial market events and the recent news coverage of China’s economic weakness, policymakers would be raising the bar at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a senior researcher at UCLA’s Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now he predicts that policymakers will wait at least a month to get a better understanding of the effects.
"The potential impact on the US economy is still very unclear and they have little information at their disposal about the consequences of what is happening in China," Oliner said.
The welfare of the international economy is not the central bank’s main concern, so in principle it should not influence decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the world’s monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the Central Bank has been enormous.
In 2013, then-chairman, Ben S. Bernanke, hinting that the central bank could “narrow” the increase in money supply caused upheavals in markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is “more art than science,” said Zachary Karabell, global strategy manager for the asset management company Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond, Virginia, noted this month that “the central bank has previously overreacted to a financial market movement that appears to be disconnected from economic fundamentals.”
The decision-making Federal Open Market Committee has called for an increase in the interest rate, and Lacker, a member of the committee with the right to vote, cites the 1998-99 decisions as an example.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its reference value by 0.75 percentage points during three meetings “despite its limited, identifiable impact on U.S. economic growth,” Lacker says.
A year later, the central bank reversed these cuts.
The central bank should only prioritize financial stability during a major crisis, such as when markets collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s rate-setting committee.
The latest upheaval does not come close to its level, Posen says.
“No one wants to see a situation where people are afraid of raising interest rates because the market is upset,” said Posen, president of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a double requirement and does not mention financial stability, and as long as that is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
