Weight loss surgery can help mildly obese diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for people with mildly obese type 2 diabetes can last for at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics will live longer after weight loss surgery than those treated by methods other than surgery.
“It takes a long time to get mortality data,” says Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote an editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
In bariatric surgery, various methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has been found to be effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most of the people in the study have been morbidly obese, with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or more.
A BMI, or weight-to-height ratio, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If your BMI is over 25, it indicates that you are overweight, and if your BMI is over 30, you are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at Min-Sheng General Hospital in Taiwan used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery and gastric bypass surgery, to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI of people who underwent surgery fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of people who were treated by means other than surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
Thirty-six percent of the people who had the surgery had a complete cure and 28 percent had a partial cure.
By comparison, in the medically treated group, diabetes was completely cured in only 1% and partially in about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides, and the “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors noted.
The researchers also monitored patients' blood haemoglobin A1c levels, which reflect blood sugar levels over the long term.
Hemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers wrote.
Post-operative hemoglobin A1c levels fell from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the medical treatment group, it remained stable at around 8%.
However, this improved “glycemic control,” which is described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels, did not reduce mortality over a five-year period, says lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research group also compared average results between two different types of surgery.
At the age of five, when compared to a group undergoing gastric bypass surgery, the group who had had gastric bypass surgery had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), had decreased more than their BMI (7.4 and 5.1), had decreased more than their hemoglobin A1c levels (3.1% and 2.1%), and were more likely to have achieved complete remission (1.6%).
Blackstone of the University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix says that while the study does not show survival or surgery after five years, there are research findings from Sweden where surgery led to longer lives for heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people who underwent weight loss surgery had a 29 percent lower chance of dying over a 15-year period when compared to a group who had tried more traditional treatments.
While the new study doesn’t show an improvement in surgical patient survival, Blackstone says the results are encouraging for people with a BMI below 35 who are interested in surgery.
“The research results are crucial precisely because they show that surgery is safe for the lower BMI group,” with no increased risk of death or kidney disease, he says.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their doctors should take weight very seriously when the patient’s BMI is between 27 and 30.
“I think we’re waiting too long before we take this seriously,” he says.
I believe that once a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it will be very difficult to reverse the situation.
