Glencore Raises $2.5 Billion to Sell Shares
The Swiss-based mining giant Glencore, which suffered from a collapse in commodity prices, raised $2.5 billion on Wednesday by selling shares as part of its vast debt-cutting plan.
Glencore, listed on the London Stock Exchange, said in a statement that it had sold up to <0xC2><0xA3>1.6 billion in new shares to reduce its debt.
The company, which lost 57% of its market value this year, is struggling with collapsed commodity prices as the slowdown in the Chinese economy strains demand and wreaks havoc on all markets.
The rights issue put Glencore’s stock price at the top of the London Stock Exchange on Wednesday mornings.
Stocks rose 2.77 percent to 131.60 pence in the FTSE 100 index, opening 0.69 percent higher.
Glencore had revealed last week a $2.5 billion stock deal as part of a broader plan to cut its $30 billion debt burden by about a third.
The company sold the new share capital for 125 pence, which meant a 2.4% discount on Tuesday’s closing price.
The company sold 1.3 billion shares worth 9.99 percent of the group.
Concerns about China’s prolonged stagnation of growth have cut iron ore prices by about half, while at the same time the prices of coal, copper and other commodities have fallen by 20 to 40 percent.
White House confirms Xi Jinping's visit to Washington
Chinese President Xi Jinping will make a state visit to the United States at the end of the month, a statement released by the White House on Tuesday confirmed.
Xi’s first official visit to Washington will take place on September 25 and is a response to President Barack Obama’s visit to Beijing last November, the statement said.
U.S. President and First Lady Michelle Obama will host a dinner for Xi and his wife Peng Liyuan after the leaders have held bilateral talks.
“The visit of President Xi will provide an opportunity to expand cooperation between the United States and China on a wide range of global, regional and bilateral issues of common interest, while at the same time enabling President Obama and President Xi to have a constructive discussion on issues of disagreement,” the statement added.
During the visit, which was first announced in February, Xi is also expected to depart for Seattle on his trip to Washington, D.C., to meet with a number of U.S. technology leaders before moving on to New York City and the UN General Assembly in September.
Obama and Xi are expected to discuss a number of controversial topics, including Washington’s concerns about China’s alleged cyber espionage and the country’s increased insistence on the South China Sea’s controversial waters.
