Xi calls for wider opening of the economy to the world
The economy needs to open up more to the outside world to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told a group tasked with steering the reform.
“China should commit to attract foreign funding and expertise and develop a policy of transparency,” he said, speaking at the 16th meeting of the group leading the deepening of the overall reform.
Supporting openness at the same time as reforms are being pushed forward will create new movement and vitality, and create new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Steering Group adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list limiting market access, a relaxation of the principles of border control, an invitation to state-owned enterprises to seize private capital, and a revision of the residents’ registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created, identifying the sectors and companies in which it is not allowed to invest.
The system will be gradually tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant as it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensures a legal business environment and makes the market more transparent.
The government also loosens its control over the power it allocates to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to run their business.
China will allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation as well as new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
In order to open up state-controlled sectors to private financiers, more sectors will open up.
“The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, the application process for permanent resident permits for foreigners, "green cards", is facilitated by optimizing the requirements and streamlining the application process.
The meeting also discussed the guaranteeing of the right to practise the profession of lawyer and support for professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang, as well as senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement released after the meeting.
